<activity><title>Stopping Distance</title>

<introduction><sidebyside widths="50% 40%"><p>The faster a car moves, the more difficult it is to stop. The graph shows the distance, <m>d</m>, required to stop a car as a function of its velocity, <m>v</m>, before the brakes were applied.</p>
  <image source="act-5-4-3.png" width="45%"></image></sidebyside></introduction>

                <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
                <p>Values of the variables are not given, but can be read from the graph.</p></commentary>

<task><p>Find a formula for <m>d</m> as a function of <m>v</m>. Hints:</p>    
    <p><ul>
    <li><p>How do you know from the graph that <m>d=kv^2</m> (instead of <m>d=kv</m> ?</p></li>
    <li><p>Use a point on the graph to find the value of <m>k</m>, and then write the formula.</p></li>
    </ul></p></task>

<task><p>How fast was the car moving if it took 50 meters to stop?</p></task>

<task><p>What is the stopping distance for a car moving at 100 kilometers per hour?</p></task>
</activity>

